:"Withington, Lancashire, England","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England"},"en":{"about 1130–":"about 1130–Deceased","1130–Male":"1130–Deceased","1135–Female":"1135–Deceased","1150–1212":"1150–1212","1110–Male":"1110–Deceased","1115–Female":"1115–Deceased","about 1150":"about 1150","1215":"1215","1115":"1115","1224":"1224","1212":"1212","1135":"1135","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","about 1130":"about 1130","Withington, Lancashire, England":"Withington, Lancashire, England","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Withington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name mainly from Withington in Lancashire and Cheshire, though occasionally from any of the other places so named in Gloucestershire, Herefordshire, Shropshire, and Staffordshire, or Witherington Farm in Standlynch (Wiltshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>wīthign</i> ‘willow, willow copse’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":85,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":94,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Withington was born about 1130, in Withington, Lancashire, England, his father, Wulfric de Withington, was 22 and his mother, Mrs Wulfric De Withington, was 17. He had at least 1 son with Matilda Musard."},"et":{"about 1130–":"umbes 1130–Surnud","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1135–Female":"1135–Surnud","1150–1212":"1150–1212","1110–Male":"1110–Surnud","1115–Female":"1115–Surnud","about 1150":"umbes 1150","1215":"1215","1115":"1115","1224":"1224","1212":"1212","1135":"1135","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","about 1130":"umbes 1130","Withington, Lancashire, England":"Withington, Lancashire, England",